Logical Operators

When we need to test for 2 or more conditions we use LOGICAL Operators

    AND OR NOT
    && || !

AND
true && true -> TRUE
true && false -> FALSE
false && true -> FALSE
false && false -> FALSE

boolean cold=true;
boolean rain=false;

if (cold && rain) { --> FALSE
        SOPln ("I will stay at home");
}

OR
true || true -> TRUE
true || false -> TRUE
false || true -> TRUE
false || false -> FALSE

if (cold || rain) { --> TRUE
    SOPln ("I will stay at home");
}

NOT - reverse the condition

    boolean boo=!false;
    System.out.println(boo); //true

Switch Statement -

syntax

switch (variable) {

case value1:
            code A;
            break;
case value2:
            code B;
            break;
default:
        Code C;
        break;
}

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

Loop - repeat block of code based on the condition

4 loops in JAVA:
USE while you don't know how many times you will repaeat the code
while
do while

USE for loop when you know in advance how many times you will repeat the code
for
for each/advanced for loop/ enhanced for loop